1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,699
Just for those of you who have not yet studied enough Pali, Sanvega is translated as enthusiasm.

2
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:11,862
Have you got another translation for enthusiasm?

3
00:00:11,942 --> 00:00:16,327
Enthusiasm?

4
00:00:17,208 --> 00:00:18,390
Is that right?

5
00:00:18,410 --> 00:00:20,071
And Pasadi is calmness.

6
00:00:24,356 --> 00:00:26,478
No?

7
00:00:26,498 --> 00:00:27,278
I thought it was confidence.

8
00:00:27,359 --> 00:00:28,381
Confidence?

9
00:00:28,400 --> 00:00:28,541
Pasadi?

10
00:00:28,561 --> 00:00:29,801
Pasadi is confidence.

11
00:00:30,608 --> 00:00:32,491
Oh, pasada.

12
00:00:32,512 --> 00:00:33,133
Oh, excuse me.

13
00:00:33,192 --> 00:00:33,793
Yes, pasada.

14
00:00:33,834 --> 00:00:34,314
Confidence.

15
00:00:34,335 --> 00:00:34,636
Excuse me.

16
00:00:34,676 --> 00:00:36,118
Yeah, yeah.

17
00:00:36,139 --> 00:00:37,322
Yeah, confidence, faith.

18
00:00:37,883 --> 00:00:38,584
Like saddha.

19
00:00:40,527 --> 00:00:43,173
Part is just a reinforcing word there.

20
00:00:43,573 --> 00:00:44,316
Great confidence.

21
00:00:47,521 --> 00:00:49,005
Well...

22
00:00:51,466 --> 00:00:56,798
The Buddha talks about these four ways of coming to know something.

23
00:00:59,203 --> 00:01:05,576
One of them is through what we hear or what we see, something coming towards us.

24
00:01:07,766 --> 00:01:29,539
You know, there are instances in the scripture where even his name, the Buddha, would say somebody like his, who became one of his main supporters, an Atapindika, just that word arose, this enormous interest, enormous, well, Samvega, this sort of enthusiasm.

25
00:01:34,480 --> 00:01:43,475
With that, when you hear something, and we'll talk just within the spiritual field, but it works with lots of things.

26
00:01:44,739 --> 00:01:58,242
When you hear something, it sort of raises an interest in you, and after you've received that sort of information, you would think about it yourself.

27
00:01:58,780 --> 00:02:12,508
So that somebody else's thought, as it were, through your own interior dialogue, becomes, as it were, your own knowledge, in a sense, your own intellectual knowledge, anyway, and understanding.

28
00:02:14,151 --> 00:02:14,792
Come on in here.

29
00:02:19,441 --> 00:02:19,741
Try to...

30
00:02:27,332 --> 00:02:39,674
We're talking about Sanvega and Pasadis.

31
00:02:42,078 --> 00:02:49,509
So you hear something which draws your interest and then having heard enough of it, you sort of think about it yourself.

32
00:02:50,771 --> 00:02:57,298
So the Buddha may have introduced you, shall we say, to his Four Noble Truths.

33
00:02:57,418 --> 00:03:00,801
You might have just been talking about suffering, the cause of suffering.

34
00:03:02,282 --> 00:03:05,605
I'm translating the word dukkha, this is going to be a Pali lesson this evening.

35
00:03:08,087 --> 00:03:12,812
I'm translating the word dukkha as suffering, unsatisfactoriness, whatever, we can come to that later.

36
00:03:15,034 --> 00:03:19,158
And it might have raised your interest, so you go away and you think about it, you see.

37
00:03:19,796 --> 00:03:24,443
And that becomes your own intellectual knowledge, as it were.

38
00:03:24,463 --> 00:03:28,009
It becomes part of your internal thinking.

39
00:03:30,334 --> 00:03:39,647
But it still hasn't got, as it were, the ring of truth in terms of experiential truth.

40
00:03:41,251 --> 00:03:47,020
And that's where the Buddha would have offered the system of investigation that we call vipassanā.

41
00:03:48,956 --> 00:04:14,205
now all the way along that line this enthusiasm you know has to be there enthusiasm is perhaps a big too big a word really and so it grows into an enthusiasm and that enthusiasm comes out of this Sada this this faith now it's translated as faith but it's just confidence

42
00:04:14,724 --> 00:04:16,487
putting one's trust in.

43
00:04:17,026 --> 00:04:28,177
So it's a sort of gradual process for somebody, shall we say, who's coming to Buddhism for the first time or indeed any religious tradition.

44
00:04:29,519 --> 00:04:31,860
If you're born into it, it's a given.

45
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:35,144
As a child you're already developed that way.

46
00:04:35,163 --> 00:04:44,512
There's no questioning or there's no need to raise faith because it's sort of within you as a child.

47
00:04:46,687 --> 00:04:57,757
But when you come to Buddhism at a different time in your life, then there has to be this sort of rather slow process of receiving that sort of information.

48
00:04:59,699 --> 00:05:13,351
And as you hear it, as you hear the Buddha's teaching and there grows in you a sort of interest towards it, that desire to take it further, you see, that's your samvega, that's your...

49
00:05:13,636 --> 00:05:38,562
energy behind it and the energy behind it rests on this slowly growing confidence in the teaching which you've which you're developing through first of all listening to what people have to say about the buddhist teaching and then thinking about it yourself but at some point it has to mature into your own

50
00:05:39,791 --> 00:05:45,708
personal experience really, or else it just remains a sort of a head level.

51
00:05:46,228 --> 00:05:53,228
It doesn't actually begin to flower, as you might say, within the heart as such.

52
00:05:56,043 --> 00:06:02,093
the Buddha gave a particular methodology that he called meditation or vipassana.

53
00:06:02,512 --> 00:06:13,029
But it's not just that, it is actually a fullness, a sort of discovery of the path in everything we do.

54
00:06:13,069 --> 00:06:18,338
So this develops into an understanding of what he then called the Eightfold Path.

55
00:06:19,668 --> 00:06:28,894
So the first part of the Eightfold Path, this right understanding, develops through these three particular ways.

56
00:06:29,596 --> 00:06:34,369
So the right understanding comes because you've listened to something, you've thought about it yourself.

57
00:06:34,771 --> 00:06:41,884
And this draws into your attitudinal, it sinks into the heart as an attitude.

58
00:06:41,944 --> 00:06:45,632
And then there's that search to make it real.

59
00:06:46,213 --> 00:06:48,357
So that's your Sambhaga, you see.

60
00:06:48,999 --> 00:06:53,387
And the joy that you get from that, from investigating.

61
00:06:54,785 --> 00:07:21,754
and the investigation then is both this process of introspection this process of examining your own psyche really and we'll come back to it in a minute and then it has to begin to express itself in the way that we speak in the way what we do and in our livelihood so it has to be a sort of systemic thing

62
00:07:23,454 --> 00:07:44,382
And this sort of systemic effect of our understanding, as it were, coils back on itself to deepen our understanding of the Buddha's teaching and a greater desire to sort of keep investigating.

63
00:07:44,362 --> 00:08:01,495
And the method of investigation in terms of the actual practice is through this vipassana, which is, I suppose, the easiest way to describe it, I think, at least to myself, is that you're...

64
00:08:01,475 --> 00:08:18,538
you're making objective everything that you thought was subjective, so just as when you walked into this room you didn't associate with it as being you, I mean it wasn't that sort of psychosis,

65
00:08:18,517 --> 00:08:23,007
And you didn't also develop an attachment to it as mine.

66
00:08:23,026 --> 00:08:31,103
So as you walked in the room you might have looked around and caught the atmosphere of the room and all that and the windows etc.

67
00:08:31,904 --> 00:08:35,952
So in a sense you're trying to find a position within yourself.

68
00:08:36,928 --> 00:09:03,914
to turn this interior room into something objective so the outer walls of your body and what you get from your body, your sensations and feelings and the atmosphere of the room, your emotional life and the thoughts that come through and as you begin to investigate that from the Buddha's perspective

69
00:09:04,908 --> 00:09:25,263
which is always to try to understand where the mistake has been made, which is actually causing us to feel either severe suffering in our lives, mental suffering or even just discomforts.

70
00:09:26,323 --> 00:09:29,649
Something is wrong with what we're actually doing.

71
00:09:30,845 --> 00:09:38,115
And that's what we're trying to investigate, you see, the technique that we're using which is causing us problems.

72
00:09:40,658 --> 00:09:45,043
As we begin to delve deeper in that, you see, two things are happening.

73
00:09:45,203 --> 00:09:55,418
First of all, you begin to actually see the Buddha's teachings for yourself and this then becomes your own personal experience.

74
00:09:56,173 --> 00:10:03,417
And with that, you get this greater sambhaga, this greater enthusiasm to keep on your investigation.

75
00:10:07,480 --> 00:10:35,073
a lot of our science is driven scientific discovery is driven by people who have that interest and then are driven by a real desire to want to know so that's your Sambhaga so the one as it were sparks off the other the more you hear which raises your interest the more you want to know

76
00:10:35,527 --> 00:10:39,673
The more you get to know, the more your faith and confidence grows.

77
00:10:40,394 --> 00:10:46,346
The more you have confidence, the more you empower decisions to continue your investigation.

78
00:10:47,326 --> 00:10:47,567
See?

79
00:10:48,308 --> 00:10:55,981
And so it rolls on, just continues to roll on like that until hopefully we're all fully liberated.

80
00:11:04,837 --> 00:11:30,815
What the Buddha, shall we say, what set him off on his path, on his own personal quest, was two things.

81
00:11:31,395 --> 00:11:34,440
First of all, there seems to have been some time in his

82
00:11:35,736 --> 00:12:02,317
young manhood where there was um a weariness a disenchantment with the pleasures of the world um it's put in the story that he's had a big party and he wakes up in the morning and he just sees you know people disheveled and they've all got drunk you know well you know what it's like

83
00:12:02,837 --> 00:12:08,905
And he thinks, well, this is sort of an empty thing, you see, just pleasure.

84
00:12:11,509 --> 00:12:16,336
Sort of an empty experience.

85
00:12:18,558 --> 00:12:32,337
Usually, there are sort of questions about sexuality and whatnot, and I always bring this up because when it comes to just sex, you see, as a pleasurable experience,

86
00:12:33,854 --> 00:12:44,109
I always like to quote Woody Allen, who said, just sex on its own is an empty experience, but as empty experiences go.

87
00:12:48,174 --> 00:13:03,337
So the Buddha, one of the things that happened to the Buddha was, as a Bodhisattva, before he was enlightened, before he was liberated, was this feeling of the vanity of trying to seek happiness in just sensual pleasure.

88
00:13:05,038 --> 00:13:05,961
That's the first thing.

89
00:13:08,647 --> 00:13:24,263
And the next thing was a much more, it was a deeper sort of experience, which was more existential in the sense that it was about the basic path that we take towards sickness, old age and death.

90
00:13:25,693 --> 00:13:32,942
So again this is put in a sort of mythological way where he comes across somebody sick, old and a corpse.

91
00:13:33,724 --> 00:13:51,027
But it's really the end game of aging and especially death which as it were puts the rest of our lives into a certain context and what with his

92
00:13:52,086 --> 00:14:12,070
feeling that all the pleasures that life could give him had an emptiness to them, added to the fact that he knew that death was at the end of the line, threw him into what we would call these days an existential crisis.

93
00:14:13,552 --> 00:14:20,259
And it was this sort of existential crisis that really drove him to seek some answers.

94
00:14:21,159 --> 00:14:42,241
He was part of a wave of what was happening, a bit like the hippies of the 70s, you know, where there were lots of men mainly, few women because it was a bit of a dangerous occupation to be wandering about on your own, trying to seek liberation.

95
00:14:44,062 --> 00:14:45,222
of one sort or another.

96
00:14:46,825 --> 00:14:48,386
And he was part of that movement.

97
00:14:48,447 --> 00:14:59,239
In fact, the Jain, the founder of the Jains, the Niganta, Nigantaputta, he was a contemporary elder of the Buddha, you see.

98
00:14:59,940 --> 00:15:07,268
So there was a whole sort of movement of the time, and it is said it's because, you know, this is what...

99
00:15:07,331 --> 00:15:13,859
the academics tell you, is because society at that time was in a bit of a turmoil, much in the same as ours was.

100
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:27,292
Moving away from a sort of pastoral, easy-go-lucky, more democratic society to a monarchical, city-based, armies with elephants, all that sort of stuff.

101
00:15:27,692 --> 00:15:30,054
And a merchant class making money.

102
00:15:31,476 --> 00:15:34,740
It was all sort of a big change going on and

103
00:15:35,767 --> 00:15:42,908
that sort of feeling of dislocation, alienation, all these lovely existential words.

104
00:15:44,373 --> 00:15:51,764
And so he himself is part of that movement and goes out to seek liberation.

105
00:15:52,144 --> 00:15:55,769
In his words, to seek the end of this dukkha.

106
00:15:55,849 --> 00:15:58,833
That's the other big word in the Buddhist teaching.

107
00:15:58,894 --> 00:16:04,761
This dukkha, actually its root meaning, it just means a hard place.

108
00:16:04,981 --> 00:16:07,686
So life's hard and then you die.

109
00:16:07,866 --> 00:16:10,330
That's what the comedians say, isn't it?

110
00:16:11,895 --> 00:16:34,932
and he's trying to find the reason for it and whether there's an escape so he works with various teachers and one of the things was to create an internal

111
00:16:35,960 --> 00:17:05,275
an internal happiness which was not dependent on an external object so it's easy to get happy on a good film ice cream and all that sort of stuff but through the practice of absorption meditation and various techniques one can build within oneself an ecstasy you don't need to have an external object and

112
00:17:07,769 --> 00:17:15,181
The techniques for that vary, but one of them would be a mantra, something repeated.

113
00:17:15,622 --> 00:17:18,385
Not just repeated, but actually greatly intended.

114
00:17:19,728 --> 00:17:26,179
And it's much the same as the technique that we use to get ourselves depressed, really.

115
00:17:27,821 --> 00:17:29,785
Where you say to yourself, I am depressed.

116
00:17:30,665 --> 00:17:31,587
I am so depressed.

117
00:17:32,489 --> 00:17:33,590
I am really depressed.

118
00:17:35,089 --> 00:17:37,458
May all beings be depressed.

119
00:17:38,361 --> 00:17:42,232
Eventually you just feel so depressed.

120
00:17:43,317 --> 00:17:45,102
If you say, may I be happy.

121
00:17:46,105 --> 00:17:47,209
May all beings be happy.

122
00:17:47,529 --> 00:17:48,373
I'll lift you a bit, you see.

123
00:17:50,580 --> 00:18:10,175
Then there's other techniques which we needn't go into at the moment, but the point was that when he learnt these things, although they created these beautiful spaces, internal spaces within him, interior, interior loveliness, they came to an end.

124
00:18:13,682 --> 00:18:35,671
He later incorporated these practices within his teachings but he saw them as unsatisfactory, they weren't actually leading to or weren't answering his deep question about how is it that we are conscious beings and we've ended up being unhappy?

125
00:18:36,692 --> 00:18:38,513
Why is that?

126
00:18:39,015 --> 00:18:40,737
And was that the way it was?

127
00:18:41,881 --> 00:19:11,330
so having left he left both of his teachers and then tried a form of self-mortification and the understanding behind self-mortification is that the problem lies in the body so all our appetites greed for food lust all these things you can say derived from the body itself so the idea was to reduce the appetites of the body

128
00:19:11,547 --> 00:19:16,598
And he went through these rather long period of mortification, it would seem.

129
00:19:18,221 --> 00:19:20,768
And he said all that did was made him suffer more.

130
00:19:21,269 --> 00:19:24,236
So he sort of abandoned that.

131
00:19:25,018 --> 00:19:27,784
And it was really...

132
00:19:28,117 --> 00:19:49,207
After that, when he's quite, he must have been feeling quite, quite depressed, having not found any answer to it, that he is sitting by the roadside, and a woman comes along with some rice pudding, and offers him that, and it sort of vivifies him.

133
00:19:51,590 --> 00:19:56,116
And of course, you all know the salvific effect of rice pudding, so...

134
00:19:56,501 --> 00:20:25,782
so with that sort of a bit of energy interestingly enough he remembers this incident in childhood now in childhood he's watching his father doing a plowing ceremony and he falls into one of these absorption states but it's not, he can't obviously be the same of these absorption states that he's learnt from these other teachers

135
00:20:26,252 --> 00:20:33,313
There was something a little, there was something in that absorption state which was something different.

136
00:20:34,356 --> 00:20:39,029
And what it was was this sense of curiosity.

137
00:20:41,068 --> 00:20:48,720
And it was from that position of curiosity that he then, this samvega arose, this enthusiasm.

138
00:20:48,799 --> 00:20:57,471
Suddenly he realized that maybe this was a way of investigating which would actually make him understand where the core problem was.

139
00:20:59,375 --> 00:21:01,557
And because of his past practice,

140
00:21:03,142 --> 00:21:30,009
and this tremendous Samvega that now came, he found a lovely place, which we now call Bodh Gaya, and under the fig tree, the religious fig tree, he sat and was sort of clear enough to say that this is it, I can't see anything else apart from this, and I'm going to sit here,

141
00:21:30,884 --> 00:21:33,208
And either I'm going to make it or I'm going to drop dead.

142
00:21:34,309 --> 00:21:34,990
I'm going to die.

143
00:21:36,192 --> 00:21:41,021
Which is one hell of a resolution when you think about it.

144
00:21:41,041 --> 00:21:46,111
Luckily for him and for us, he actually makes it within about six hours.

145
00:21:46,351 --> 00:21:47,272
That's what it says.

146
00:21:47,894 --> 00:22:04,063
And within that insight he sort of cracks the problem really as to where the root mistake has been made.

147
00:22:06,490 --> 00:22:16,787
And just for those of you who don't know, just to finish the story, he then of course goes through it and he's very clear about what it is that he's come to understand.

148
00:22:17,267 --> 00:22:19,391
And then there's that desire to teach.

149
00:22:19,490 --> 00:22:22,035
That's the compassion that arises.

150
00:22:23,298 --> 00:22:27,144
the anu kaupā, which translates as moving towards the other.

151
00:22:29,067 --> 00:22:32,211
So, and then of course begins his career.

152
00:22:32,571 --> 00:22:44,170
There's a moment of doubt, which is again put mythologically as the Brahma Sahampati comes down and asks him, you know, that there are people with little dust in their eyes who can understand.

153
00:22:45,211 --> 00:22:50,519
And then off he goes to seek his five companions who'd left him

154
00:22:51,107 --> 00:23:06,567
when he'd given up those mortifications and that's it and that's the beginning of his teaching career so this word liberation

155
00:23:08,336 --> 00:23:34,412
he's liberated himself from what he calls this dukkha and this dukkha has three components to it it's the first of all the relationship that we have to things that we don't like anyway and if you observe yourself you'll see that you're constantly moving towards comfort

156
00:23:35,522 --> 00:23:44,115
even sitting here you might just catch yourself, as soon as there's some small discomfort in the body, there's a shift, there's a move, there's a constant...

157
00:23:44,904 --> 00:23:48,630
There's a constant effort to try and move away from what is uncomfortable.

158
00:23:49,651 --> 00:23:52,434
Now you might say, well, of course, that's absolutely understandable.

159
00:23:53,457 --> 00:23:55,519
Why would I want to sit in discomfort?

160
00:23:56,340 --> 00:24:10,660
Well, obviously we should not sit in discomfort just for the sake of it, but it's the underlying understanding which is making us do that which is at fault here.

161
00:24:12,074 --> 00:24:24,260
And the fault lies in, you could say, psychologically anyway, is in seeking happiness in sensual pleasure, seeking happiness in this world that we experience.

162
00:24:25,387 --> 00:24:34,469
And what we find of course is that that happiness is entirely dependent upon what you experience and you can't control your experience.

163
00:24:34,809 --> 00:24:43,650
So you might feel happy at this particular point and then somebody says a rude word to you and then you feel unhappy.

164
00:24:43,630 --> 00:24:57,512
So because we're living in a world which isn't following our dictates, then we're constantly finding ourselves having to try to manipulate the world, try and do something with it in order to establish this happy mind.

165
00:25:00,577 --> 00:25:06,346
So this constant seeking happiness in the world actually, paradoxically, puts us into conflict with it.

166
00:25:08,503 --> 00:25:11,811
So you've got two positions there.

167
00:25:11,892 --> 00:25:25,482
First of all, those things that we are drawn towards, which we find actually make us happy, calm, peaceful and all that, because we rated happiness as being a mental state,

168
00:25:26,762 --> 00:25:31,829
We're therefore dependent upon that which is creating our mental state.

169
00:25:31,849 --> 00:25:33,872
And therefore we tend to hold on to it.

170
00:25:33,892 --> 00:25:34,653
It's quite logical.

171
00:25:34,693 --> 00:25:39,440
You want to hold on to your money and your friendships and all that.

172
00:25:40,060 --> 00:25:42,403
So that's what we mean by this sense of attachment.

173
00:25:42,644 --> 00:25:47,651
It's driven by this wrong search for happiness.

174
00:25:49,353 --> 00:25:54,660
And it lies in this mistake that happiness is some form of mental state, some emotional state.

175
00:25:56,057 --> 00:25:59,980
But there's never a time when an emotional state is ever steady.

176
00:26:01,863 --> 00:26:06,946
You can't steady even your emotional states, even if you were to try.

177
00:26:07,788 --> 00:26:08,868
They keep changing.

178
00:26:12,952 --> 00:26:22,681
There's an obvious reason for that, which is the second reason for this unsatisfactoriness, is that everything is in a process of change.

179
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:25,103
Everything is moving, everything...

180
00:26:25,318 --> 00:26:32,730
What was disappears and what is doesn't hang about much and we just hope that something will be that makes us happy.

181
00:26:33,451 --> 00:26:47,074
So when we actually drive ourselves to the immediate reality that we live in we find there's not much there really because it's in this constant movement, constant change.

182
00:26:47,881 --> 00:26:55,511
So the idea of trying to hold something still, you know, get the world to stop, is ridiculous.

183
00:26:58,241 --> 00:27:13,159
And the fact that we try and do that, the fact that we try to hold things, you know, this is it, you know, this is the way we want it to be, the way a relationship, we form a relationship with somebody and that's the way we want it to remain, you know, you're not the person I married, that sort of stuff.

184
00:27:13,640 --> 00:27:22,410
You see, all that doesn't take into account that you can't stop change, you can't stop this constant movement.

185
00:27:24,517 --> 00:27:36,971
And the other thing which undermines any hope, really, of trying to establish a permanent happiness in the sensual world is that everything is dependent on something else.

186
00:27:37,451 --> 00:27:41,936
So even from that point of view, we don't have any control.

187
00:27:43,258 --> 00:27:51,688
So if I get great joy out of DVDs and my DVD player breaks down, it's a catastrophe, isn't it?

188
00:27:53,186 --> 00:27:56,272
My TV breaking down, you know, something like that.

189
00:27:56,874 --> 00:28:01,002
So, and a TV is dependent on all the little bits and parts.

190
00:28:02,005 --> 00:28:07,234
It's dependent upon the DVD itself.

191
00:28:07,756 --> 00:28:13,827
I mean, when you begin to actually investigate the situation we're in,

192
00:28:14,128 --> 00:28:18,055
We're totally dependent on something else.

193
00:28:18,375 --> 00:28:24,525
So this body is dependent on air, dependent on food, something so basic like that.

194
00:28:26,106 --> 00:28:38,787
So trying to establish something which has such an interconnectedness with everything around us, trying to hold that, trying to maintain it, it's a big job, isn't it?

195
00:28:43,238 --> 00:28:57,594
So you can see that this understanding of unsatisfactoriness comes not so much not because of the way things are but because of our relationship to the way things are.

196
00:29:02,299 --> 00:29:05,663
And that relationship manifests in two very simple ways.

197
00:29:06,324 --> 00:29:10,308
You either hold on to what you've got at all costs

198
00:29:10,558 --> 00:29:30,778
or you try and get rid of what you don't like and that splits also into sort of a fork because either you try to annihilate that which is uncomfortable or you run for it so those are your three those are our three basic positions

199
00:29:30,961 --> 00:29:34,805
one of holding, attachment, greed, etc.

200
00:29:35,484 --> 00:29:40,569
and one of aversion which is either pushing away or running for it.

201
00:29:48,217 --> 00:29:54,823
So the question is from what the Buddha began, the question is how do we get out of that?

202
00:29:55,604 --> 00:29:59,667
How do we find, and if you do get out of that relationship

203
00:30:00,086 --> 00:30:29,232
what is the new relationship and what do you end up what sort of relationship are you moving towards you see so partly with the vipassana with the practice of vipassana it's to understand those movements within our psyche which is where the problem lies and we begin to as it were having seen more clearly

204
00:30:29,922 --> 00:30:37,211
the idea that everything that I'm experiencing, everything that I thought was me is actually in a process of change, never mind the world.

205
00:30:39,275 --> 00:30:44,382
This body is in a process of continuous change, continual change.

206
00:30:44,402 --> 00:30:48,587
The mind is in a continual, it's not the same mind you were born with, is it?

207
00:30:48,607 --> 00:30:49,750
The one that we've got now.

208
00:30:49,789 --> 00:30:57,059
And any relationship I have to what I'm experiencing of holding on

209
00:30:57,479 --> 00:31:25,613
and of pushing away, I'm just getting myself into a confusion, I'm just getting myself into a constant conflict, see, and I try and bury all that, I just fling myself onto the couch, fall asleep, or roll over when the alarm goes, it just gets too much, see, so even that becomes an escape, trying to find some sort of escape in oblivion, you see, which is great, there's no suffering in oblivion, right,

210
00:31:28,006 --> 00:31:30,729
It's just you wake up.

211
00:31:30,749 --> 00:31:32,289
That's the problem.

212
00:31:32,309 --> 00:31:34,051
You could disappear forever.

213
00:31:35,394 --> 00:31:37,875
But in Buddhist understanding, that's not possible.

214
00:31:44,903 --> 00:31:56,275
So understanding that psychology takes us to a sort of deeper level, which is about identity.

215
00:31:57,148 --> 00:32:24,355
and that really takes us to the core problem and this is where this teaching about anattā, this not-self arises and the Buddha's technique is not to make some sort of metaphysical statement there is no self or there is anything like that what he's saying is when you look into yourself and look at your experiences

216
00:32:25,178 --> 00:32:52,468
can you truthfully say this is me this is me and what the meditation is doing is drawing you into a position of the objective observer within yourself and from that position of an observation post within yourself you can begin to observe what you're experiencing as an object now

217
00:32:54,067 --> 00:33:02,221
as you look at me now, your vision is filled with me, my face etc.

218
00:33:02,942 --> 00:33:14,962
but you can also become aware of the space between us and that space is the detachment, is the distance

219
00:33:15,414 --> 00:33:36,106
So this also within yourself when you, as it were, sense a sensation in your body or an emotion, you see, as soon as you've made it an object, you've also created a space, a mental space between that which knows, your intelligence, your intuitive intelligence, and what it is you're experiencing.

220
00:33:37,369 --> 00:34:05,689
that separation you see is the experience of not me not mine because in that space you can point to what it is you're experiencing and say well there is that which experiences or knows and what it is experiencing and knowing and that little separation is an experience of not me not mine see as you then

221
00:34:06,833 --> 00:34:22,125
pull back to that position and feel yourself to be the witness, the observer, the feeler, the experiencer, there is still a sense of a me, the one who experiences, the one who feels, the one who...

222
00:34:22,679 --> 00:34:32,532
And it's really cracking that one that eventually takes us to that position of no self at all, you see.

223
00:34:33,253 --> 00:34:34,355
No sense of a me.

224
00:34:34,775 --> 00:34:42,867
And in our meditation, you know, when everything's very quiet, you can even make that your object.

225
00:34:43,327 --> 00:34:47,413
You can even make that sense of self an object.

226
00:34:47,432 --> 00:34:49,715
The fact that you're aware of yourself

227
00:34:51,349 --> 00:34:57,677
The fact that you have this self-awareness, even now you can be aware of yourself listening to me, see?

228
00:34:57,697 --> 00:35:03,483
Even the fact that you're aware of yourself means you can't be the self you're aware of.

229
00:35:04,005 --> 00:35:08,590
It's already an object.

230
00:35:08,610 --> 00:35:17,019
Even as you sit within yourself and sometimes you clear everything out and you get a great sense of presence, a sense of being, right?

231
00:35:19,025 --> 00:35:20,967
So it's a sense of being.

232
00:35:21,347 --> 00:35:22,429
You can't be that.

233
00:35:24,432 --> 00:35:28,518
We'd like to be that, but you can't be what you're aware of.

234
00:35:31,061 --> 00:35:31,643
Tricky one, isn't it?

235
00:35:33,505 --> 00:35:36,869
So then the question arises, well, who the hell am I?

236
00:35:38,813 --> 00:35:43,800
And it's driving your investigation to answer that question, which...

237
00:35:44,759 --> 00:36:10,918
allows us to have this final experience of what the Buddha called Nibbāna even if it's only an inkling of it even if it's only a little insight and that's your liberation now this word Nibbāna is rather interesting there are various explanations there are various attempts to try to find its meaning

238
00:36:11,927 --> 00:36:14,431
Etymology is sort of root meaning.

239
00:36:15,494 --> 00:36:19,780
And various writers and teachers plumb for one or the other.

240
00:36:20,601 --> 00:36:24,268
Some say it's some sort of the losing of heat.

241
00:36:24,809 --> 00:36:29,056
It's a sort of cooling process.

242
00:36:29,456 --> 00:36:31,199
Cooling the suffering is cooling.

243
00:36:32,021 --> 00:36:36,568
But the one that I particularly like is unshackled.

244
00:36:38,016 --> 00:36:53,961
And there are two reasons we call that, because it seems as though that is a root meaning of the word Nibbāna, but also because in the process of our liberation, we get rid of what's known as the fetters, is what the Buddha called them, the fetters.

245
00:36:55,844 --> 00:37:01,594
And there are ten of these fetters, we don't have to go into them in any great detail,

246
00:37:02,974 --> 00:37:12,269
but the one that's of interest is the fetter that this personality is who I am.

247
00:37:13,731 --> 00:37:29,657
Now, although we would all desire to have our 15 minutes of ecstatic celebrity, the fact is that when you look into your personality, your character,

248
00:37:30,581 --> 00:37:36,791
You find that it's just made up of particular attitudes, of particular characteristics.

249
00:37:37,773 --> 00:37:39,175
The one dependent on the other.

250
00:37:39,635 --> 00:37:42,338
A lot of it dependent on the situation you're in.

251
00:37:43,121 --> 00:37:52,614
You don't know, for instance, how courageous you are until a situation demands that you be courageous.

252
00:37:53,014 --> 00:37:56,320
You know, often we think of people who've been caught up...

253
00:37:56,688 --> 00:38:08,525
in prisons, Tibetan monks and people who were caught up by Islamic extremists in the Middle East a few years ago.

254
00:38:09,467 --> 00:38:12,371
And everybody asked them, how did you have the strength to go through it?

255
00:38:12,632 --> 00:38:17,639
And invariably they say things like, well, you just find it.

256
00:38:17,940 --> 00:38:19,101
Everybody's got it within them.

257
00:38:19,722 --> 00:38:22,025
Although I know some people didn't fare so well.

258
00:38:22,827 --> 00:38:25,311
But the fact is, you don't know

259
00:38:25,864 --> 00:38:35,733
where you are in terms of your virtues and so on, until the situation demands it of you, you see.

260
00:38:38,197 --> 00:38:45,664
So one of the insights that you are released of is that you are not that.

261
00:38:46,985 --> 00:38:55,213
Even your personality, your character is something which is developing, changing, dependent on and so forth.

262
00:38:55,952 --> 00:39:10,552
the other one is the understanding that rites and rituals won't get you very far in terms of the process of liberation and although that doesn't mean to say that you can't have rites and rituals you just put them in the right perspective

263
00:39:11,275 --> 00:39:14,378
they're there really to create an ambience, an effect.

264
00:39:14,800 --> 00:39:25,974
So, you know, you walk into a beautiful temple and it has a certain atmosphere and ambience, it has a certain scent to it, you know, sandalwood, candles and all that.

265
00:39:26,335 --> 00:39:32,724
But no matter how much you bow to the Buddha statue or light many candles, it's not going to get you that far.

266
00:39:32,945 --> 00:39:37,130
It might make you feel good, but it's not going to get you that far.

267
00:39:37,702 --> 00:39:43,693
So this unshackling, see, this unshackling of what?

268
00:39:44,795 --> 00:39:47,000
It's the unshackling of this intelligence, isn't it?

269
00:39:47,581 --> 00:39:51,188
Unshackling the intelligence, this intuitive intelligence, from what?

270
00:39:51,969 --> 00:39:55,076
From its misunderstandings, its delusions.

271
00:39:57,500 --> 00:40:00,485
So if we reverse that process...

272
00:40:00,853 --> 00:40:06,643
this intelligence finds itself within this psychophysical organism.

273
00:40:07,364 --> 00:40:08,927
I like saying that.

274
00:40:08,947 --> 00:40:15,097
It finds itself within this psychophysical organism and it's quite understandable that it should say, well, this is what I am.

275
00:40:15,858 --> 00:40:16,739
This is what I am.

276
00:40:18,242 --> 00:40:26,916
And within that, within the experience of this, of being a human being, we try to make, we try to create heaven.

277
00:40:27,597 --> 00:40:28,498
It's understandable, isn't it?

278
00:40:30,588 --> 00:40:37,657
And it's only when we fail and end up feeling quite miserable that we think, well, there might be, maybe I'm getting something wrong, you see.

279
00:40:38,960 --> 00:40:41,603
And that's, of course, when you search for meditation.

280
00:40:44,047 --> 00:40:57,608
And then you begin to reverse that process of undoing the wrong identities and the wrong search for happinesses and slowly, as it were, pull back

281
00:40:58,516 --> 00:41:03,501
from that commitment you had to this life form, thinking that this was going to deliver.

282
00:41:05,965 --> 00:41:09,668
Now you might say, well, that's all well and good, so where does that lead us?

283
00:41:10,349 --> 00:41:15,976
You end up being a sort of amorphous blob, having left your body, society and all that.

284
00:41:17,057 --> 00:41:18,840
What's the end game of that?

285
00:41:20,842 --> 00:41:27,190
Well, paradoxically, it leads you back into an engagement.

286
00:41:28,300 --> 00:41:37,331
So first of all we find ourselves in an engagement which is causing us problems causing us to suffer, feel alienated etc.

287
00:41:37,351 --> 00:41:37,811
etc.

288
00:41:38,612 --> 00:41:54,172
We then go through this process of pulling out of that which feels sometimes like a loss you might have enjoyed a few glasses of wine and then you realize that getting inebriated is not quite the path

289
00:41:55,519 --> 00:42:04,672
And so you have to pull out of those areas where you were finding at least some sort of temporary happiness.

290
00:42:06,074 --> 00:42:14,186
And as you do that, of course, you have to re-establish a new relationship with the world that we find ourselves in.

291
00:42:16,646 --> 00:42:43,920
so this is manifested as a transformation of our former attitudes so whereas the world was there to feed us, the world was there to make us happy that's turned around in a relationship of wanting to make the world feel happy

292
00:42:44,659 --> 00:42:47,849
So what was selfishness now becomes generosity.

293
00:42:48,650 --> 00:42:57,335
And that's a very different relationship where you're not demanding anything of the world and yet in helping others you find your joy.

294
00:43:00,032 --> 00:43:21,398
Whereas once you've found yourself in contradiction with the world, a hatred with the world, you then re-establish one which is looking upon others and the world itself as friendships, as friendliness, and all the virtues you would expect of a friend.

295
00:43:22,900 --> 00:43:23,661
Care and stuff.

296
00:43:25,277 --> 00:43:45,115
And that relationship of friendship or goodwill, perhaps that's the best translation of the word meta, goodwill, you can see that compassion, the desire to help where it's needed, arises naturally, as you would with any friend.

297
00:43:46,036 --> 00:43:53,563
And sympathetic joy, to rejoice in other people's good fortune and so on, arises naturally from that basis of goodwill.

298
00:43:56,512 --> 00:44:05,949
So whereas once even those acts of goodwill had within them some sort of kink of self-regard

299
00:44:06,925 --> 00:44:30,333
Even acts of compassion were driven also by perhaps some unacknowledged desire to please oneself, now become much more true acts of compassion and with it there comes as a return a real pure joy.

300
00:44:30,313 --> 00:44:58,902
so just take a very simple example if somebody's you know if somebody says to you would you you know a friend says you know I've just got a new apartment a new flat you know you know would you like to come and do a bit of painting for me so he says oh it's fine love to do it you see so you go over there but there's a sort of underlying small print you know when I need a bit of help you will come to help me see

301
00:45:00,907 --> 00:45:23,996
and of course when your friend doesn't well what sort of friend is that is it and so all the time even when we're actually doing something at a conscious level which feels to us to be compassionate joyful etc we're sometimes not aware of these subliminal demands that we're making

302
00:45:25,072 --> 00:45:34,105
and these more subtle demands, remember are always turning the other into an object to please us.

303
00:45:34,911 --> 00:45:36,054
That's what you're doing, isn't it?

304
00:45:36,173 --> 00:45:51,233
Every time I do something with some unwritten contract underneath that you will come to please me, I turn you into something to please me, I turn you into an object.

305
00:45:51,614 --> 00:45:55,800
I lose that sense of you being a human being.

306
00:45:58,304 --> 00:46:01,307
That's what attachment does, doesn't it?

307
00:46:01,327 --> 00:46:01,407
Hmm?

308
00:46:04,864 --> 00:46:09,333
When it comes to things like loneliness.

309
00:46:09,994 --> 00:46:20,914
So loneliness is driven by an internal feeling of perhaps not being loved or not being wanted or something like that.

310
00:46:21,695 --> 00:46:23,277
It's not a pleasant feeling.

311
00:46:25,063 --> 00:46:55,054
normally speaking we wouldn't want to stay within that atmosphere so we call a friend and tell them a bit lonely tonight and they're lonely so why don't we go out together and create company and then our sense of joy of being with somebody is an escape from really looking at the causes of our loneliness and we think that the cure of loneliness is simply more society

312
00:46:55,590 --> 00:47:22,677
but then you get bored with your mate, with your friend and you get into this seeking company at all costs now if we were then instead to sink into that feeling of loneliness to come to feel it, to come to actually experience it fully within ourselves for no other reason than but to allow it to express itself

313
00:47:22,945 --> 00:47:38,887
we may find to our surprise that once it begins to exhaust its energy, as it were, no matter how nasty the feeling is, it very slowly, as it were, moves towards its own transformation.

314
00:47:40,588 --> 00:47:46,336
And that transformation we call solitude, just being at one with oneself.

315
00:47:48,494 --> 00:47:54,364
And that works really with all the negative states that we have.

316
00:47:54,664 --> 00:48:06,244
To be able to sit with it, not as a thought pattern, very careful here you see, if you sit with it as a thought pattern, it is unwittingly developing itself.

317
00:48:06,264 --> 00:48:13,438
Because it's through thought and imagination that our emotional states develop themselves.

318
00:48:16,202 --> 00:48:31,911
I mean, even on an obvious sort of negative level, you know, if somebody says something to you in the morning which has upset you slightly, but you brushed it away, you haven't really looked at that, you've just brushed it away as being nothing to worry about.

319
00:48:32,793 --> 00:48:39,746
And then in one unguarded moment over the morning cup of tea, you're saying, how could that bloody...

320
00:48:41,380 --> 00:48:51,375
and you're eating and biting your fork when you're eating, stop, stop, stop, and by evening you take an aspirin.

321
00:48:52,777 --> 00:48:54,360
You've got to overcome the headache that you've got.

322
00:48:54,559 --> 00:49:01,170
This person's only insulted you once, but you've been at it all day, repeating the insult, making it, churning it over.

323
00:49:01,190 --> 00:49:08,501
Then you begin to realize, oh, what the mind is doing is churning, you see, it's just churning, just stirring the whirlwind.

324
00:49:09,206 --> 00:49:21,387
So when we want to really heal ourselves of all this negativity within us, we find the answer lies actually within the body, within that emotional state.

325
00:49:22,389 --> 00:49:32,025
And it's sinking into it and sitting with it and bearing it and allowing it to express itself no matter how awful it might be, you know.

326
00:49:32,005 --> 00:49:50,436
dreadful anxieties, even at worst things like suicidal feelings, just to stay with that and let the heart speak its pain, as it were, which it does through feeling, and to just stay there patiently, and to attend to it.

327
00:49:51,360 --> 00:50:21,266
to attend to it you can even attend to it with a sense of compassion you can even flavor your attention with a little warmth a little for a better word a little hug just to embrace your own suffering and in so doing you're allowing this I mean what is it what is it when you go down and feel an emotion and you've taken away its word

328
00:50:21,382 --> 00:50:28,798
When you've taken away the word depression, when you've taken away the word anxiety, and you go into the feeling of it, what is it?

329
00:50:29,641 --> 00:50:30,422
What do you come up with?

330
00:50:31,706 --> 00:50:34,431
You come up with very different words.

331
00:50:34,532 --> 00:50:38,360
Heaviness, burning, agitation.

332
00:50:39,521 --> 00:50:52,659
and it's coming off that conceptual mind completely and entering into the feel, into the actual feel of an emotional state, that paradoxically allows it to expend its energy.

333
00:50:53,380 --> 00:51:04,094
And in so doing, you may be fortunate enough, it's not always obvious, you may actually experience that transformation.

334
00:51:04,074 --> 00:51:18,693
where suddenly that restlessness drops and you're completely at calm, where the hatred has turned and you feel in a very loving state, where the loneliness suddenly disappears and you're perfectly happy within yourself.

335
00:51:20,835 --> 00:51:23,780
Not to say that these states do not arise again.

336
00:51:23,800 --> 00:51:28,445
I wouldn't want to give anybody false hope.

337
00:51:31,041 --> 00:51:48,349
So that business of liberation is both a conceptual liberation, a beginning to understand where our concepts have led us, where our presumptions have led us.

338
00:51:49,710 --> 00:51:53,757
It has to be driven more deeply into the heart base.

339
00:51:53,777 --> 00:51:58,905
It must be driven into what we call our emotional mental state life.

340
00:51:59,407 --> 00:52:09,545
And there, there's seemingly no other way out than to bear, than to allow the heart to speak its problems.

341
00:52:10,206 --> 00:52:21,788
And if you don't, it'll come out through the body anyway, in psychosomatic upsets, back pain, headaches and so on, even severe disease.

342
00:52:28,552 --> 00:52:39,449
And it's only then, through that process, that we begin to experience how it might be, you see.

343
00:52:39,469 --> 00:52:46,661
How it might be, if I can just move this different relationship, if I can find a different relationship to life.

344
00:52:47,704 --> 00:52:48,666
how it might be.

345
00:52:49,226 --> 00:53:00,403
And that's where, going back to our earlier question, you get this surge of interest, this desire to carry on, to want to take this process to an end.

346
00:53:02,728 --> 00:53:15,686
So it's that process of understanding, of the practice, of seeing how the liberation comes, which moves you to further practice, further investigation.

347
00:53:20,054 --> 00:53:32,213
Just a point of clarification, are you implying that back pain, headaches and serious disease all emerge from the same origin?

348
00:53:32,954 --> 00:53:33,094
No.

349
00:53:33,134 --> 00:53:37,240
The body itself, as you know, has its own, well, intelligence is not a better word.

350
00:53:39,844 --> 00:53:42,748
And we can't say that all illnesses obviously come from that.

351
00:53:42,789 --> 00:53:47,016
I mean, obviously one of them is asbestosis, you know, the disease you get from breathing in asbestos.

352
00:53:47,717 --> 00:53:47,817
Okay.

353
00:53:47,864 --> 00:54:09,248
but the suffering of course that arises when we get a disease like that is also self-generated that's not caused by the disease but by our relationship to disease and life etc and really that's where I think the the

354
00:54:10,206 --> 00:54:21,135
as we say, the cutting edge of investigation is most profitable, is to see, be constantly aware of our relationship to what it is that we're experiencing.

355
00:54:22,177 --> 00:54:34,407
And to just be awake to whenever we're holding on to something, you know, to really catch the conversation that's going on beneath the obvious.

